How do I interpret user needs and implement them into a program? How does creating “user stories” help with this?
In a school setting, I interpret user needs primarily through the rubric. It gives me a broad sense of what the user is looking for, and then I can dig into the
specific conditions within each section. For example, a rubric category like "User Validation" might include more detailed requirements such as "validate that 
the user enters a number" or "display an error message when incorrect input is given." That helps me build a user story around those ideas—something like: "As 
a user, I want an error message when I provide incorrect input so that I understand what went wrong and can fix it when prompted again." This approach does more 
than just outline the feature; it gives me the reasoning behind it. I realize I’m not just supposed to flag bad input—I need to explain why it's wrong, which in 
turn helps clarify what kind of input the program actually expects. That deeper understanding leads to a much better final product.

How do I approach developing programs? What Agile processes do I hope to incorporate into my future development work?
In my future school projects, I plan to take an iterative approach when working on assignments. I'll start by creating a sort of "product backlog" when I first 
review the project requirements, listing out everything that needs to be done. Then each day, I'll select a few items to focus on—treating those as my sprints. 
This way, I can make sure every aspect gets completed by the due date without feeling like I have to tackle the whole project in one sitting. It will also help 
me get better at judging how long tasks take, since I'll have a clearer sense of how similar work has gone for me in the past.



What does it mean to be a good team member in software development?
To be a good team member in software development, I need to listen, contribute, and continuously develop myself. By truly listening to my coworkers and the client,
I can better understand what actually needs to be done, which helps me focus my energy on what matters instead of getting sidetracked by things that aren't important. 
That listening naturally leads into the contributing aspect of the job. Even as an entry-level team member, my input still matters—good ideas can come from anyone, 
and speaking up helps build a stronger project. At the same time, if I offer a suggestion that someone else disagrees with, I need to listen to their reasoning so I 
can either adjust my thinking or have a productive conversation about why my idea might still work. Finally, I have to keep developing myself. Programming languages 
and technology are always evolving, and it's my responsibility to keep learning so I can continue offering better contributions to my team and building better products 
for my clients.
